Write a program to check whether a given number is an Automorphic number or not.

A number is called an Automorphic number if the square of the number ends with the same digits as the number itself.

For example:

5² = 25 → ends with 5 ✅ → Automorphic Number

6² = 36 → ends with 6 ✅ → Automorphic Number

25² = 625 → ends with 25 ✅ → Automorphic Number

7² = 49 → does not end with 7 ❌ → Not Automorphic

Input Format

A single integer n

Constraints

n >= -100000

Output Format

If the number is an Automorphic number, print Automorphic Number or Not an Automorphic Number

---------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------

#include <stdio.h>
#include <string.h>
#include <math.h>
#include <stdlib.h>

int main() {
    int n;
    scanf("%d", &n);

    int square = n * n;        // Step 1: find the square of the number
    int temp = n;              // Step 2: copy n to count digits
    int digits = 0;

    // Step 3: count how many digits are in n
    while (temp > 0) {
        digits++;
        temp /= 10;
    }

    // Step 4: extract the last 'digits' digits of square
    int divisor = 1;
    for (int i = 0; i < digits; i++) {
        divisor *= 10;
    }

    int last_digits = square % divisor;

    // Step 5: compare last digits with original number
    if (last_digits == n)
        printf("Automorphic Number");   // Automorphic
    else
        printf("Not an Automorphic Number");    // Not Automorphic

    return 0;
}
